A class is declared with the following instance variable declarations and no constructor:

```java
private int count;
private double total;
private boolean active;
private String label;
```

Which of the following correctly lists the default values of `count`, `total`, `active`, and `label` for a newly created object?

Consider the following class and code segment.

```java
public class Box
{
    private int width;
    private int height;

    public Box(int w, int h)
    {
        width = w;
        height = h;
    }

    public int getArea()
    {
        return width * height;
    }

    public int getPerimeter()
    {
        return 2 * width + 2 * height;
    }
}
```

```java
Box b = new Box(4, 6);
System.out.println(b.getArea() + " " + b.getPerimeter());
```

What is printed?

Consider the following class.

```java
public class Counter
{
    private int count;

    public Counter(int count)
    {
        count = count;
    }

    public int getCount()
    {
        return count;
    }
}
```

A student writes `Counter c = new Counter(5)` and then calls `c.getCount()`. Which of the following best describes what happens?

Consider the following class and code segment.

```java
public class Product
{
    private String name;
    private double price;

    public Product(String n, double p)
    {
        name = n;
        price = p;
    }

    public String toString()
    {
        return name + ": $" + price;
    }
}
```

```java
Product p = new Product("Widget", 9.99);
System.out.println(p);
```

What is printed?

Consider the following class.

```java
public class Widget
{
    private static int count = 0;
    private int id;

    public Widget()
    {
        count++;
        id = count;
    }

    public int getId()           { return id;    }
    public static int getCount() { return count; }
}
```

After executing the following code, what are the values returned by `w1.getId()` and `Widget.getCount()`?

```java
Widget w1 = new Widget();
Widget w2 = new Widget();
Widget w3 = new Widget();
```

Consider the following class and code segment.

```java
public class Roster
{
    private ArrayList<String> names;

    public Roster(ArrayList<String> n)
    {
        names = n;
    }

    public ArrayList<String> getNames()
    {
        return names;
    }
}
```

```java
ArrayList<String> myList = new ArrayList<String>();
myList.add("Alice");
myList.add("Bob");
Roster r = new Roster(myList);
myList.add("Charlie");
System.out.println(r.getNames().size());
```

What is printed?

Consider the following class and code segment.

```java
public class Rectangle
{
    private int length;
    private int width;

    public Rectangle(int length, int width)
    {
        this.length = length;
        this.width  = width;
    }

    public void scale(int length)
    {
        this.length = this.length * length;
    }

    public int getLength() { return length; }
    public int getWidth()  { return width;  }
}
```

```java
Rectangle r = new Rectangle(4, 3);
r.scale(2);
System.out.println(r.getLength() + " " + r.getWidth());
```

What is printed?

